## Data
For the homework, we will use data about vertebrate home range sizes. The data are in the class folder, but the reference is below.  

**Database of vertebrate home range sizes.**  
Reference: Tamburello N, Cote IM, Dulvy NK (2015) Energy and the scaling of animal space use. The American Naturalist 186(2):196-211. http://dx.doi.org/10.1086/682070.

Herbivore

```r
mean(herbivore.animals$mean.hra.m2, na.rm=T)
```

Carnivore

In comparison herbivores have a larger mean, 'mean.hra.m2'
 
**9. Make a new dataframe `deer` that is limited to the mean mass, log10 mass, family, genus, and species of deer in the database. The family for deer is cervidae. Arrange the data in descending order by log10 mass. Which is the largest deer? What is its common name?**  



```r
deer <-select (homerange, "log10.mass", "family", "genus", "mean.mass.g")
deer.cervidae <-filter (deer, family =="cervidae")
deer.cervidae
```

```
##    log10.mass   family      genus mean.mass.g
## 1     5.48746 cervidae      alces   307227.44
## 2     4.79812 cervidae       axis    62823.19
## 3     4.38112 cervidae  capreolus    24050.27
## 4     5.37062 cervidae     cervus   234757.78
## 5     4.46909 cervidae     cervus    29450.32
## 6     4.85400 cervidae       dama    71449.63
## 7     4.13033 cervidae  muntiacus    13499.88
## 8     4.73130 cervidae odocoileus    53864.17
## 9     4.94391 cervidae odocoileus    87884.04
## 10    4.54407 cervidae ozotoceros    35000.16
## 11    3.87506 cervidae       pudu     7499.98
## 12    5.00885 cervidae   rangifer   102058.69
```


```r
arrange (deer.cervidae, log10.mass)
```

```
##    log10.mass   family      genus mean.mass.g
## 1     3.87506 cervidae       pudu     7499.98
## 2     4.13033 cervidae  muntiacus    13499.88
## 3     4.38112 cervidae  capreolus    24050.27
## 4     4.46909 cervidae     cervus    29450.32
## 5     4.54407 cervidae ozotoceros    35000.16
## 6     4.73130 cervidae odocoileus    53864.17
```

The largest deer is the Alcels and its common name is the moose
